                    <h2 class="section__title">
                        Criminal Law <br>

                    </h2>

                    <p class="recently__description">
                        Criminal law is concerned with laws pertaining to violations of the rule of law or public
                        wrongs. Criminal law is governed under the <a
                            href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Penal_Code" class="link"> <i>Indian Penal Code,
                                1860</i> </a> Indian Penal Code, 1860, and the <a class="link"
                            href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_of_Criminal_Procedure_(India)"> <i>Criminal
                                Procedure
                                Code, 1973</i> </a> . The Indian Penal Code, 1860 , defines the crime, its nature, and
                        punishments whereas
                        the Criminal Procedure Code, 1973, defines exhaustive procedure and punishments of the crimes.
                        <br>

                        Murder, rape, theft, and assault are all examples of criminal offences under the law.
                    </p>

                    <a href="https://blog.ipleaders.in/criminal-law-in-india/" class=" button small__button">
                        Read More<i class="ri-arrow-right-line"></i>
                    </a>


                </div>

                <img src="/assets/img/criminal_lawPic.jpg" alt="recently image" class="recently__img">
            </div>

            <div class="about__container container grid">
                <div class="about__data">

                    <h2 class="section__title about__title">
                        <div>
                            Civil Law

                        </div>


                    </h2>

                    <p class="about__description">
                        Matters of disputes between individuals or organisations are dealt with under Civil Law. Civil
                        courts enforce the violation of certain rights and obligations through the institution of a
                        civil suit. Civil law primarily focuses on dispute resolution rather than punishment. The act of
                        process and the administration of civil law are governed by the <a
                            href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_of_Civil_Procedure_(India)" class="link">
                            <i>Code of Civil Procedure, 1908</i>
                        </a> .
                        Civil law can be further classified into Tort law, Family Law, Property Law, and Contract law.
                        <br>

                        Some examples of civil law are defamation, breach of contract, and a dispute between landlord
                        and tenant.
                        <br><br>
                    </p>
                    <a href="https://blog.ipleaders.in/civil-law/" class=" button small__button">
                        Read More<i class="ri-arrow-right-line"></i>
                    </a>
                </div>

                <img src="/assets/img/civil_imgae.jpg" alt="aboout image" class="about__img">
            </div>

            <div class="recently__container container grid">
                <div class="recently__data">

                    <h2 class="section__title">
                        Common Law <br>

                    </h2>

                    <p class="recently__description">
                        A judicial precedent or a case law is common law. A law passed by the Supreme Court will be
                        obligatory upon the courts and within the territory of India under <a
                            href="https://www.legalserviceindia.com/legal/article-6023-doctrine-of-precedent-article-141-.html"
                            class="link"><i>Article 141</i></a> of the Indian Constitution. A common law theory, Natural
                        justice, often known as “Jus Natural,” encompasses statutory provisions for justice. Nemo judex
                        in causa sua (Rule against Prejudice), audi alteram partem (Rule of fair Hearing), and reasoned
                        decision are the rules of Natural Justice.
                    </p>

                    <a href="https://blog.ipleaders.in/common-law-apply-india/" class=" button small__button">
                        Read More<i class="ri-arrow-right-line"></i>
                    </a>


                </div>

                <img src="/assets/img/commonlaw.jpg" alt="recently image" class="recently__img">
            </div>

            <div class="about__container container grid">
                <div class="about__data">

                    <h2 class="section__title about__title">
                        <div>
                            Statutory Law

                        </div>


                    </h2>

                    <p class="about__description">
                        Statutory legislation refers to any written law approved by a legislative body to regulate the
                        conduct of its citizens. The Central Government makes laws through Parliament, the state
                        government makes laws through Vidhan Sabha, and the Local Government makes laws through
                        municipalities. A bill is introduced in the legislature and for it to become an act voted upon
                        by the members of both houses requires the assent of the President. The President of India has
                        veto powers over his assent.
                        <br><br>
                    </p>
                    <a href="https://planetoflaw.com/statutory-laws-in-india/" class=" button small__button">
